<tr><td></td><td>LOCATION--Planet surface</td></tr>
<tr id="L44"><td><a href="#L44">44</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: They beam down in front of a vaguely castle-styled wall which is completely smooth. The locals are dressed in romanticised rural mediaeval-style clothing, and take no notice of them at all.</td></tr>

<tr id="L45"><td><a href="#L45">45</a></td><td>KIRK:  You'd think they had people beaming down every day.</td></tr>

<tr id="L46"><td><a href="#L46">46</a></td><td>SPOCK:  Yes. Curious lack of interest. Notice the ruins in the distance, Captain. Quite large.</td></tr>

<tr id="L47"><td><a href="#L47">47</a></td><td>KIRK:  Yes. A fortress, perhaps. A castle.</td></tr>

<tr id="L48"><td><a href="#L48">48</a></td><td>SPOCK:  Whatever it is, it would seem to be inconsistent with the reports we've been given on this culture.</td></tr>

<tr id="L49"><td><a href="#L49">49</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: A man in a loose purple robe opens his arms wide.</td></tr>

<tr id="L50"><td><a href="#L50">50</a></td><td>AYELBORNE:  Welcome.</td></tr>

<tr id="L51"><td><a href="#L51">51</a></td><td>KIRK:  Reception committee?</td></tr>

<tr id="L52"><td><a href="#L52">52</a></td><td>SPOCK:  It would seem so.</td></tr>

<tr id="L53"><td><a href="#L53">53</a></td><td>AYELBORNE:  You are our visitors. Welcome, welcome. I am Ayelborne.</td></tr>

<tr id="L54"><td><a href="#L54">54</a></td><td>KIRK:  I am Captain James T. Kirk of the starship Enterprise, representing the United Federation of Planets. This is my first officer Mister Spock.</td></tr>

<tr id="L55"><td><a href="#L55">55</a></td><td>AYELBORNE:  You are most welcome, my friend.</td></tr>

<tr id="L56"><td><a href="#L56">56</a></td><td>KIRK:  I would like to speak to someone in authority.</td></tr>

<tr id="L57"><td><a href="#L57">57</a></td><td>AYELBORNE:  We don't have anybody in authority, but I am the chairman of the Council of Elders. Perhaps I would do.</td></tr>

<tr id="L58"><td><a href="#L58">58</a></td><td>KIRK:  You people are in great danger. Is there someplace we can go and talk?</td></tr>

<tr id="L59"><td><a href="#L59">59</a></td><td>AYELBORNE:  Oh, yes. Our council chambers are nearby. Please.</td></tr>

<tr id="L60"><td><a href="#L60">60</a></td><td>SPOCK:  Captain, if you don't mind, I should like to wander about the village and make some studies.</td></tr>

<tr id="L61"><td><a href="#L61">61</a></td><td>AYELBORNE:  Of course, my friend. Our village is yours. Captain.</td></tr>

<tr><td></td><td>LOCATION--Council Chamber</td></tr>
<tr id="L62"><td><a href="#L62">62</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: Ayelborne and four other older men seat themselves at a simple wooden table. Beautifully polished, though.</td></tr>

<tr id="L63"><td><a href="#L63">63</a></td><td>KIRK:  Gentlemen, my government has informed me that the Klingons are expected to move against your planet with the objective of making it a base of operation against the Federation. My mission, frankly, is to keep them from doing it.</td></tr>

<tr id="L64"><td><a href="#L64">64</a></td><td>AYELBORNE:  What you're saying, Captain, is that we seem to have a choice between dealing with you or your enemies.</td></tr>

<tr id="L65"><td><a href="#L65">65</a></td><td>KIRK:  No, sir. With the Federation, you have a choice. You have none with the Klingons. The Klingons are a military dictatorship. War is their way of life. Life under the Klingon rule would be very unpleasant. We offer you protection.</td></tr>

<tr id="L66"><td><a href="#L66">66</a></td><td>CLAYMARE:  We thank you for your altruistic offer, Captain, but we really do not need your protection.</td></tr>

<tr id="L67"><td><a href="#L67">67</a></td><td>AYELBORNE:  We are a simple people, Captain. We have nothing that anybody could want.</td></tr>

<tr id="L68"><td><a href="#L68">68</a></td><td>KIRK:  You have this planet and its strategic location. I assure you that if you don't take action to prevent it, the Klingons will move against you as surely as your sun rises. We will help you build defences, build facilities.</td></tr>

<tr id="L69"><td><a href="#L69">69</a></td><td>AYELBORNE:  We have no defences, Captain, nor are any needed.</td></tr>

<tr id="L70"><td><a href="#L70">70</a></td><td>KIRK:  Gentlemen, I have seen what the Klingons do to planets like yours. They are organised into vast slave labour camps. No freedoms whatsoever. Your goods will be confiscated. Hostages taken and killed, your leaders confined. You'd be far better off on a penal planet. Infinitely better off.</td></tr>

<tr id="L71"><td><a href="#L71">71</a></td><td>AYELBORNE:  Captain, we see that your concern is genuine. We are moved. But again we assure you we are in absolutely no danger. If anybody is in danger, you are, and that concerns us greatly. It would be better if you returned to your ship as soon as possible.</td></tr>

<tr id="L72"><td><a href="#L72">72</a></td><td>KIRK:  You keep insisting there's no danger. I keep assuring you there is. Would you mind telling me</td></tr>

<tr id="L73"><td><a href="#L73">73</a></td><td>AYELBORNE:  It is our way of life, Captain.</td></tr>

<tr id="L74"><td><a href="#L74">74</a></td><td>KIRK:  That's the first thing that would be lost! Excuse me, gentlemen. I'm a soldier, not a diplomat. I can only tell you the truth.</td></tr>

<tr id="L75"><td><a href="#L75">75</a></td><td>AYELBORNE:  If you will excuse us, Captain, we will discuss your kind offer.</td></tr>

<tr id="L76"><td><a href="#L76">76</a></td><td>KIRK:  Certainly.</td></tr>

<tr id="L77"><td><a href="#L77">77</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: The doors open on their own and Spock enters. He and Kirk whisper in a corner.</td></tr>

<tr id="L78"><td><a href="#L78">78</a></td><td>SPOCK:  Captain, our information on these people and their culture was not correct. This is not a primitive society making progress toward mechanisation. They are totally stagnant. There is no evidence of any progress as far back as my tricorder can register.</td></tr>

<tr id="L79"><td><a href="#L79">79</a></td><td>KIRK:  That doesn't seem likely.</td></tr>

<tr id="L80"><td><a href="#L80">80</a></td><td>SPOCK:  Nevertheless, it is true. For tens of thousands of years, there has been absolutely no advancement, no significant change in their physical environment. This is a laboratory specimen of an arrested culture.</td></tr>

<tr id="L81"><td><a href="#L81">81</a></td><td>KIRK:  Thank you, Mister Spock. That might be useful.</td></tr>

<tr id="L82"><td><a href="#L82">82</a></td><td>AYELBORNE:  We have discussed your offer, Captain. Our opinion is unchanged. We are in no danger. We thank you for your kind offer of assistance, although we must decline it, and we strongly recommend that you leave Organia before you yourselves are endangered.</td></tr>

<tr id="L83"><td><a href="#L83">83</a></td><td>KIRK:  Gentlemen, I must get you to reconsider. We can be of immense help to you. In addition to military aid, we can send you specialists, technicians. We can show you how to feed a thousand people where one was fed before. We can help you build schools, educate the young in the latest technological and scientific skills. Your public facilities are almost non-existent. We can help you remake your world, end disease, hunger, hardship. All we ask in return is that you let us help you. Now.</td></tr>

<tr id="L84"><td><a href="#L84">84</a></td><td>AYELBORNE:  Captain, I can see that you do not understand us. Perhaps</td></tr>

<tr id="L85"><td><a href="#L85">85</a></td><td>KIRK:  (answering communicator) Excuse me, sir. Kirk here.</td></tr>

<tr id="L86"><td><a href="#L86">86</a></td><td>SULU:  Captain, a large number of Klingon vessels have just arrived.</td></tr>

